{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Hanawa Hokiichi | honorific_suffix = | image = Hanawa Hokiichi.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = 塙 保己一 | native_name_lang = ja | birth_name = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth date|1746|06|23}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and age|1821|10|07|1746|06|23}} | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = Japanese | other_names = | occupation = Scholar | period = Edo | known_for = Buddhist monk | title = | boards = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation--> | spouse = | children = | awards = <!--notable national level awards only--> | website = | education = | alma_mater = <!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution--> | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | era = | discipline = History, literature, medical science and jurisprudence | sub_discipline = <!--academic discipline specialist area – e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist--> | workplaces = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions--> | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | footnotes = }}
{{Japanese name|Hanawa}}
{{nihongo|'''Hanawa Hokiichi'''|塙 保己一||23 June 1746 &ndash; 7 October 1821}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] famous blind scholar and buddhist monk of the [[Edo period]].
Hokiichi became blind when he was 5 years old.<ref>''Japan Encyclopedia'', Harvard University, 2002, p. 285.</ref> He learned history, literature, medical science and jurisprudence from several masters. One of them was [[Kamo no Mabuchi]]. Hokiichi compiled "[[Gunsho Ruijū]]" (群書類従 Great collection of old documents).<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Hanawa Hokiichi and ''Monumenta Japonica Historica'' |title=The Oxford History of Historical Writing: 1400-1800 |last=Rabasa |first=José |author2=Andrew Feldherr |author3=Daniel R. Woolf |author4=Grant Hardy |pages=90–91 |year=2012 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780199219179 }}</ref>
In 1937, [[Helen Keller]] came to Japan and visited Hokiichi's memorial house. She expressed her impression as follows: "When I was a child, my mother told me that Mr. Hanawa should be my role model. To visit this place and touch his statue was the most significant event during this trip to Japan. The worn desk and the statue facing down earned more respect of him. I believe that his name would pass down from generation to generation like a stream of water.<ref>[http://www.onkogakkai.com/english_page.htm English page of Hanawa Hokiichi Shiryoukan]</ref>
